Caption:
The Battle Of The Mind - 

Have you ever had a negative thought?

And did you just accepted it without even thinking about where it came from?

If so, your not alone. 

Did you know?

You don‚Äôt just have to accept every thought that falls into your head.

That‚Äôs where this Bible verse comes in. 

‚Äú We demolish arguments and every pretension that sets itself up against the knowledge of God, and we take captive every thought to make it obedient to Christ.‚Äù

We must take our thoughts captive and make them obedient to Christ.

We need to check if that thought is aligned with Gods thoughts.

Is our thinking aligned with Gods way of thinking?

Is that thought true and is it even from you?

If it does not align with Gods thoughts and it‚Äôs not from you, don‚Äôt accept the thought and talk back to the enemy 

You can say in your mind or out loud ‚ÄúNo, I do not accept that thought, that is not true, it‚Äôs a lie.‚Äù

 Example - 

You have a thought that you will never have your own family or you will never really succeed in 

You DON‚ÄôT have to accept those thoughts. 

Satan is the father of lies, so how does he deceive someone? He lies to them.

The first lie ever recorded in history was by satan when he lied to Eve in the garden of Eden.

Definition of deceive - to deliberately cause ( someone ) to believe something that is not true, especially for personal gain.

 Where does satan deceive us the most? 

In our minds

After you have recognized that the thought you just had is a lie from the enemy, you can pray for the Holy Spirit to help you recognize when you have thoughts that are not from you or from God.

Always pray for God to reveal the truth/contrary to what satan tells you.

Fill your mind with good thoughts by reading the Bible! 

Don‚Äôt be defeated and remember that God has already won the battle.

‚Äú I have told you these things, so that in me you may have peace. In this world you will have trouble. But take heart! I have overcome the world.‚Äù 
John 16:33

Caption:
Yesterday, a heartwarming celebration took place in honor of International Children's Day in the village of Narodychi, just 18 miles from the Belarus border in Ukraine's Zhytomyr region. Organized by the Victory Church in Korosten and the iCare team, the event drew 120 children and over 200 attendees including families who enjoyed the festivities.

Each child received a special gift‚Äîa children‚Äôs Bible, symbolizing hope and enlightenment. The celebration also provided the attendees with a hot meal prepared by a mobile kitchen and fresh bread provided by the Korosten Bread of Life bakery.

The day was filled with smiles and a strong sense of community, offering a respite and a moment of pure joy for the village as they came together to celebrate their children and their future.

Please pray for the future of Ukraine and learn more about how you can support our other children's ministries this summer at the link in our bio.

Caption:
Trusting Jesus is an everyday thing ‚ù§Ô∏è

If I am being honest Trusting God has been so hard lately. Circumstances, disappointments and mental health struggles have been overwhelming. 

The struggles in life can cause us to question our faith or can cause us to strengthen it. We can turn away from God or turn to God, from truth to lies. 

Trusting God as a Christian is not just the moment we accept and believe the Gospel, rather it is a daily choice. A choice we make everything single moment. 

Jeremiah 17:7-8
‚ÄúBut blessed is the one who trusts in the LORD, whose confidence is in him. They will be like a tree planted by the water that sends out its roots by the stream. It does not fear when heat comes; its leaves are always green. It has no worries in a year of drought and never fails to bear fruit.‚Äù 

When we truly trust God in every moment, our faith is will become rooted in God, rooted in truth. That when we face hardships, trials, heartbreaks, hurts our faith is not be shaken. Our faith will be so strongly rooted in God. 

The more we choose to trust God, the more we renew our minds in truth the easily it will become. The quicker our heart and mind will be able to recall the truth and rest in God.

The Gospel is a matter of first importance. Rest in Jesus Christ and be saved today! #repentandbelieve 

‚ÄúCome to Me, all who are weary and heavy-laden, and I will give you rest. Take My yoke upon you and learn from Me, for I am gentle and humble in heart, and you will find rest for your souls. For My yoke is easy and My burden is light.‚Äù ~Matthew‚Ä¨ ‚Ä≠11‚Ä¨:‚Ä≠28‚Ä¨-‚Ä≠30‚Ä¨ ‚Ä≠NASB19995

Caption:
(A nun with a baby // art by me.)

In my childhood, I dreamt of becoming a nun, drawn to the peaceful and contemplative life they led. Although my path took a different turn, the presence of nuns continues to inspire me in my creative pursuits. Their dedication to service, their inner strength, and their unwavering faith serve as a guiding light, infusing my work with a sense of purpose and tranquility. The lessons I learned from their commitment to spirituality and compassion resonate deeply within me, shaping my artistic endeavors and reminding me of the beauty that can be found in simplicity and devotion.

Caption:
Ubwami bw‚ÄôImana niki? 

Ubwami bugomba kugira:
- Imipaka
- Ubukungu
- Ingabo zirinda ubwami (Ingabo)
- Umuco
- Umwami
- Abanyagihugu
- Amategeko‚Ä¶.

Mu bwami, ibintu byose ni iby‚Äôumwami harimo n‚Äôabantu. Muri republika ibintu ni ibyabaturage. Ubwami bw‚ÄôImana rero bwujuje ibyangombwa byose by‚Äôubwami ariko butandukanye mubutegetsi bwabwo n‚ÄôUmwami.

Ubwami bwa Yesu ntibugira imipaka, ahantu hose ibyaremwe bikoraho aho ni ubwami bwe kandi, turi abana (Yohana 1: 10-13) n‚Äôabenegihugu b‚Äôubwo Bwami.

Ubwami bw‚ÄôImana ni ishingiro ry‚Äôubutumwa bwiza bwa Yesu Kristo. Imana yahishuye ubwami bw‚ÄôImana muburyo 2:

- Ubwami bwo mw‚Äôijuru (Matayo 5:20)
- Ubwami bw‚ÄôImana (Luka 17: 20-21

Itegekonshinga ry‚ÄôUbwami bw‚ÄôImana riboneka muri Matayo 5: 1-12.

Niyo mpamvu Yesu atugira inama yo kubanza gushaka ubwami bw‚ÄôImana (Matayo 6:33). Tugomba kumenya uburenganzira ninshingano zacu mubwami. Bitabaye ibyo tuhinduka imbata mubwami bw‚ÄôImana aho kuba abana.

What is the kingdom of God?

A kingdom must have:
- Territory
- Resources (Economy)
- Forces protecting the kingdom (Army)
- Culture
- King
- Citizens
- Laws‚Ä¶.

In a kingdom, everything belongs to the king including the people. In a republic things belong to the people. So the kingdom of God meets all credentials of a kingdom but differs in its ruling and King.

Jesus‚Äôs kingdom has no boundaries, wherever creation touches is part of His kingdom and we are children (John 1:10-13) and citizens of this Kingdom.

The Kingdom of God is the core of the Good news of Jesus Christ. God revealed the Kingdom of God in 2 ways:

- The kingdom of heaven (Matthew 5:20)
- The kingdom of God (Luke 17:20-21

The constitution of the Kingdom of God is found in Matthew 5:1-12.

This is why Jesus advises us to seek first the Kingdom of God (Matthew 6:33). We need to know our rights and responsibilities in the Kingdom otherwise we will become slaves in the Kingdom of God instead of children.

Caption:
Have you prayed yet today?

‚ÄúEvery one of us needs half an hour of prayer a day, except when we are busy‚Äîthen we need an hour.‚Äù
- St. Francis de Sales

As a mother to four young children under 6 years old, my days are often busy and 100 miles an hour. Moving from one need to the next, often with overlapping needs. What a joy to be entrusted with so many blessings and responsibilities! And also what a daunting task. Their lives are literally in my hands, and that is why it is important to keep refining myself and learning what it means to live out our Faith. Spiritual warfare is real, y‚Äôall. The final battle is with the family, and that means it is being waged in our own homes. We must be fierce defenders. ‚ÄúI can do all things through him who strengthens me.‚Äù (Philippians 4:13) 

It is a fruit of uniting myself to Christ that I am able to better discern the next steps of my day, and as such more efficiently serve those entrusted to my care. Thus, more time because I haven‚Äôt wasted time tripping over my own two feet. I need to get out of my own way. ‚ÄúHe must increase, but I must decrease.‚Äù (John 3:30) 

Another signal grace is that I have more peace, because I am more closely united to Him. I don‚Äôt waste time wondering if what I‚Äôm doing is the right thing. I am confident that my hands and feet are in service exactly where He wants me. ‚ÄúIf any of you is lacking in wisdom, ask God, who gives to all generously and ungrudgingly, and it will be given you.‚Äù (James 1:5)

And what about the days this doesn‚Äôt happen? Those are the times when I do not unite myself to Him first thing in the morning so that my day is properly centered and ordered. Those are the days I have forgotten Him and chosen myself and my own way. ‚ÄúI am the vine, you are the branches. Those who abide in me and I in them bear much fruit, because apart from me you can do nothing.‚Äù (John 15:5)

He awaits you. He has prepared the way for you. He knows exactly where He wants you today, and He is ready and willing to tell you all about it. ‚ÄúYour word is a lamp to my feet and a light to my path.‚Äù (Psalm 119:105)

Will you pray today?

‚ÄúDeacons are the servants of charity.‚Äù - #PopeFrancis

On Thursday, May 30th, Osman Enrique de la Hoz Escorcia CSB and Eduard Alexis Guerrero Carillo CSB were ordained as deacons in the San Basilio Parish of the Archdiocese of Medell√≠n. The ordination was presided over by the Archbishop of Medell√≠n, Monsignor Ricardo Tob√≥n.

The ordination ceremony was attended by Fr. Pedro Mora CSB, as the delegate of the Superior General, and Fr. Juan Carlos Rojas Ramos CSB, Superior of San Basilio in Colombia. Also present were the Basilian priests: Fr. Carlos Rodr√≠guez, Fr. Javier Higuera, and Fr. Alberto Rodr√≠guez.

The newly ordained #deacons were accompanied by their families, coming from the Arboleda and Barranquilla regions of Colombia, as well as guest priests from the archdioceses of Bogot√° and Medell√≠n, missionaries from Parma, and friends of the Congregation.

As described in the Acts of the Apostles, seven deacons were selected to assist the Apostles in their work of serving widows and the poor. St. Stephen, a martyr, was the first deacon to be selected to serve the charitable causes of the early #Church.

The diaconate is a pivotal step in the process of ordination into the priesthood. Deriving from the Greek word ‚Äúdiaconia‚Äù ‚Äì meaning ‚Äúservice‚Äù ‚Äì only priests and deacons can read the Gospel, baptize, and witness marriages. Deacons cannot hear confessions, preside over #Mass, or anoint the sick.

We congratulate Osman and Eduard on this important milestone in their Basilian journey and wish them a blessed and fruitful ministry.

Caption:
No words can describe how much i love you Jesus..no words!! I‚Äôm relieved that you can see and feel my heart,
my good soul and how grateful i am for everything that you‚Äôve done for me. SO SO SO grateful.

I have sinned many times for so long,i almost destroyed my self hitting bottom..i knew that i was going into a very dark path,so for the first time in my life,i called your name crying and drunk asking for your help,you didn‚Äôt made me wait..
i feel asleep,and the next morning,i felt lighter,
and didn‚Äôt wanna drink anymore after years of bad habits,i was lazy,but from that morning no day passed by that
 I didn‚Äôt work out.
I removed all fake and envy people around me and started fresh all by myself! 
My head became clearer and I saw all the red flags around me,from people,to habits and places.
Everyday I become stronger and faster.

You never left my side,even when I was sinning and cursing all day. You always protected me from dangerous situations,VERY  dangerous.
I was blind,and influenced by the evil,thanks to you I had always this gut feeling that I was doing the wrong things,but I couldn‚Äôt find the courage to change‚Ä¶.until I was FED UP!
You always blessed me,from birth and in every single aspect of my life. You did AMAZING things for me,so grateful!
I‚Äôll be nothing without you,I‚Äôm trying my best to live the life how you wish and command..is not easy but is worth the pain! 
I‚Äôm honored to call you my savior,my king,my everything.
Cannot wait to hug you.

In other words, some sort of external force with very dark and devious motives. üêç I was also taught that the only way to combat this force was to be in relationship with God, whose power supersedes that of said enemy. In other words, my attention was directed away from my own inner world‚Ä¶ my ego, desires, sexuality, experiential processing etc and focused firmly on ‚Äúspiritual‚Äù realities. I was taught (indirectly, allegorically) that my inner world couldn‚Äôt really be trusted, that it constantly needed to be in ‚Äúsubmission‚Äù to God and His will for my life. Which, interestingly, could only be deciphered with the help of other spiritual ‚Äòauthorities‚Äô. 

This spirituality was what was most valued and noticed in me by those around me. In the meantime, my family environment was volatile because most of us lacked the tools to be able to navigate and regulate our own emotions and feelings. Faith was just supposed to trump everything, and now I realise so much of my daily experiences were unnecessarily  spiritualised. 

Now, it‚Äôs so obvious to me that this didn‚Äôt set me up well for dealing with the complexity of life, and I see this dynamic being perpetuated in church‚Ä¶ which is triggering. I was forced to reckon with that ignorance on a new level when I got married, and I‚Äôve been on a GOOD journey of self-discovery and growth since. 

I‚Äôve realised that often, my greatest enemy is really the narratives I tell myself, about myself - positive AND negative. On one end, there is a whole bunch of negative self-talk (interesting that this seems to be automatic for so many of us), self-shaming and judgement. On the other‚Äî pride, ego, selfishness etc. 

When the faith traditions we‚Äôre involved in fail to validate these things as THE HUMAN CONDITION through dialogue and exploration, and instead add MORE judgement, shame and unrealistic behavioural expectations to the mix, the result can be üí£ [septic]. 

So, I get quite passionate about this stuff. üòù We‚Äôve been discussing these themes over on @wearebadpeople_ podcast and this poem was born as a result of our chats üéßü§ç

Our God is ‚Äúnot slow to fulfill his promises as some count slowness, but is patient towards you, not wishing that any should perish, but that all should reach repentance.‚Äù 2 Peter 3:9 

Be patient. God isn‚Äôt finished with you yet.

Caption:
It's absolutely essential to safeguard the purity of the church, foster unity within the community, and ensure that our message is impactful. When we encounter individuals who sow discord, it's crucial to address the issue directly instead of brushing it aside. If someone is spreading rumors or causing conflict, it's important to confront the situation and encourage them to communicate directly with the person they're talking about. Even if they don't take our advice and perhaps even turn against us, it's important to remember that their actions are not aligned with Christ's teachings. They are closed off to learning and may use deceptive tactics such as smooth talk and flattery to serve their own hidden agendas.

As Christians, our responses and attitudes should revolve around Christ and his Church. We should aim for obedience, humility, a generous spirit, accountability, contentment, service, growth in our faith, maturity, and a strong desire to fulfill God's will. While we're here on earth, we need to remain watchful against the influence of evil. We must hold fast to our faith, stand firm, fight the good fight, and never give up.

Have you ever thought about how many images your eyes process daily?

A team of neuroscientists at MIT discovered the human brain can process complete images the eye views for as little as 13 milliseconds. A millisecond is 1/1000 of a second. A hummingbird flaps its wings 200 times in one second.

Going to work. In the grocery store. Scrolling on our phones. 

Our brain absorbs every image we even glance at.

18 In hope he believed against hope, that he should become the father of many nations, as he had been told, ‚ÄúSo shall your offspring be.‚Äù 19 He did not weaken in faith when he considered his own body, which was as good as dead (since he was about a hundred years old), or when he considered the barrenness[b] of Sarah's womb. 20 No unbelief made him waver concerning the promise of God, but he grew strong in his faith as he gave glory to God, 21 fully convinced that God was able to do what he had promised. 22 That is why his faith was ‚Äúcounted to him as righteousness.‚Äù 23 But the words ‚Äúit was counted to him‚Äù were not written for his sake alone, 24 but for ours also. It will be counted to us who believe in him who raised from the dead Jesus our Lord, 25 who was delivered up for our trespasses and raised for our justification.

Let us be unwavering in our faith today that God will fulfill all of His promises.

Once Jesus arrived in heaven, he was given power and authority by his heavenly Father, as his reward for being obedient till death!  Philippians 2:9-11 clearly states this!  1Corinthians 15:24-28 talks about what will happen after Jesus' thousand year reign over a perfected, fully restored, righteous new earth, where righteous humans will dwell.  At that time, when all is completed, Jesus will give all power and authority back to his God and Father, JEHOVAH!
Revelation 1:1 was written, long after Jesus' death, resurrection, and ascension to heaven. It clearly states that Jehovah gave Jesus a revelation, Jesus gave that revelation to one of his angels, that angel then passed that revelation onto John, which John then revealed to us!! It's just another hole in the life of a donut!

Caption:
2 Corinthians 5:21 - God made him who had no sin to be sin for us, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God. NIV

If we‚Äôre to become something we‚Äôve never been, i.e. the righteousness of God, such means the doing of something we‚Äôve never done, i.e. the renouncing of sin.

For that is who we‚Äôve been, what we‚Äôve become, sinners stuck under this sun apart from the Son which came to shine some sense into our midst as if to save us from ourselves as sold to those sins which have come to become us so very definitely and definitively and defiantly that He had to descend into our darkened dwellings designed by these deceitful desires that we‚Äôve devoted the entirety of our time to trying and testing and tasting to see what we think is good, convinced that we know what is good despite our pasts proving we knowing nothing of the matter.

And thus something new had to be done as all we‚Äôve done is ruin everything from reality to responsibility alongside our frantic fleeing from faith for fear of the failure that such opportunity offers.

And as a people of almost perfect fear and defiant doubt, we're a people who would otherwise stay in this place surrounded by such worthless wins as everything a world gives for the simple sake of not having to lose what we can't allow ourselves to admit we've already lost.

Thankfully God's not quite so quick to give up as we've become!

In fact, He's instead willing to do what He knew we never would. He moved toward us, came for us, knowing that our sins and the death within them would keep us from striving for the gift of new life, eternal life that He's always wanted for us.

Yes, He knew we never knew to want it for ourselves. And so He came to take our death so that we might see that His way of life found for all of eternity is indeed worth dying for.

Beforgedbyfaith.blogspot.com

Caption:
June 3
 
SURE-FOOTEDNESS

‚ÄúThe Lord God is my strength, and he will make my feet like hind‚Äôs feet, and he will make me to walk upon mine high places.‚Äù Habakkuk 3:19
 
This confidence of the man of God is tantamount to a promise; for that which faith is persuaded of is the purpose of God. The prophet had to traverse the deep places of poverty and famine, but he went down hill without slipping, for the Lord gave him standing. By-and- by he was called to the high places of the hills of conflict; and he was no more afraid to go up than to go down.
See! the Lord lent him strength. Nay, Jehovah Himself was his strength.
Think of that: the Almighty God Himself becomes our strength!

Note, that the Lord also gave him sure-footedness. The hinds leap over rock and crag, never missing their foothold. Our Lord will give us grace to follow the most difficult paths of duty without a stumble. He can fit our foot for the crags, so that we shall be at home where apart from God we should perish.
One of these days we shall be called to higher places still Up yonder we shall climb, even to the mount of God, the high places where the shining ones are gathered. Oh, what feet are the feet of faith, by which, following the Hind of the Morning, we shall ascend into the hill of the Lord! #christianity #jesus #christian #faith #bible #god #gospel #bibleverse #godisgood #love
